One of it&#39;s most common uses is when you use a variable in a method/function that has the same name as another class-level variable.

In this case (no pun intended) using the `this` keyword will tell the copmiler that you&#39;re referring to the class&#39;es variable.

 An example:

    public class Customer
    {
        public string Id { get; set; }
        public string Name { get; set; }

        Public Customer (string Name, string Id)
        {
            this.Name = Name; //&quot;this.Name&quot; is class&#39;es Name and &quot;Name&quot; is the constructor&#39;s parameter.
            this.Id = Id; // Same for the Id
        }
    }
       
&lt;br&gt;

[MSDN Doc for further reading and other uses][1]


&lt;br&gt;

Also, a small sidenote, ID should always be stored as a `string`, since `int` has the maximum value of `2147483648` and ID&#39;s are treated as a string anyway (you never use math on it like `Id++` or `Id = Id * 2` for example).

(Of course I&#39;m referring to state ID&#39;s like &quot;6480255197&quot; and not &quot;1&quot;, &quot;2&quot; and so on)


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/keywords/this

